entry.tran: 可以区别开的;可以辨明的
entry.def: If something is distinguishable from other things, it has a quality or feature which makes it possible for you to recognize it and see that it is different.

example.ex: ...features that make their products distinguishable from those of their rivals...
example.tran: 使他们的产品区别于竞争对手产品的特色

example.ex: This is vintage port, and it is distinguishable by its deep red colour.
example.tran: 这是佳酿葡萄酒，它有特别的深红色。

entry.def: If something is distinguishable, you can see or hear it in conditions when it is difficult to see or hear anything.

example.ex: He put his ear to the floor and heard angry shouts, but no words were distinguishable...
example.tran: 他把耳朵贴在地板上，听到了怒吼，但是听不清所说的内容。

example.ex: It was getting light and shapes were more distinguishable.
example.tran: 天亮起来了，万物变得更清晰了。

means.word_mean: 1. capable of being perceived as different or distinct;

sentences.sentence: "only the shine of their metal was distinguishable in the gloom"
"a project distinguishable into four stages of progress"

means.word_mean: 2. (often followed by `from') not alike; different in nature or quality;

sentences.sentence: "the word `nationalism' is used in at least two distinct senses"
"a tree related to but quite distinct from the European beech"
"management had interests quite distinct from those of their employees"
